h deterministic 'no KB hit' detection, the critical failure is generation quality: real LLMs may still hallucinate instead of issuing a disclaimer. A stubbed model would miss this. Rejected Workflow because this behavior evaluates one agentic output conditioned on a single upstream state (no relevant KB entries), not a multi-agentic sequence dependency.","test_description":"Force KB retrieval to return no relevant entries, then generate with a real model and assert presence of required disclaimer language and absence of unsupported factual claims across repeated runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.68,"Workflow":0.07}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The approval workflow blocks sending until the user explicitly approves — no draft is sent automatically.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is cross-module control flow (state machine/UI approval gate + send service invocation). It does not require real network/OS to catch the failure; in-process wiring with a fake sender can expose premature sends. Rejected System because behavior text is about gating logic, not real SMTP/API transport behavior.","test_description":"Execute approval-state transitions in an integrated test harness with a spy/fake send adapter; verify no send call occurs before explicit approval event and exactly one send occurs after approval.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.64,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full sequence — read thread, generate draft, check facts, present for approval — works end-to-end for a real email thread.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"The behavior explicitly requires a multi-step pipeline, and at least one step (draft generation) is agentic. Correctness depends on chained step outputs (thread read -> generation -> fact check -